message.content:
A common iguana is a reptile that belongs to the family Iguanidae.
It has a large body with a long tail and strong legs.
Its skin is covered with overlapping scales that vary in color from green to brown.
A distinctive feature of the common iguana is the spines that run along their backs and tails.
They have a triangular head with a crest of spiky scales on their necks.
Common iguanas are herbivorous and can be found in tropical regions of Central and South America as well as some Caribbean islands.
They are often kept as pets and can be seen in zoos and reptile exhibits.
